04487nam a22006975i 9781501724251DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017242517 a10.7591/97815017242512doi  a(DE-B1597)515439  a(OCoLC)1083587154  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN56.F35bF76 2002 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a809/.933582211 aFrost, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSex Drives :bFantasies of Fascism in Literary Modernism /cLaura Frost. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b12 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. "Fascinating Fascism" -- tChapter 1. Fascism and Sadomasochism: The Origins of an Erotics -- tChapter 2. The Libidinal Politics of D. H. Lawrence's "Leadership Novels" -- tChapter 3. The Surreal Swastikas of Georges Bataille and Hans Bellmer -- tChapter 4. Beauty and the Boche: Propaganda and the Sexualized Enemy in Vercors's Silence of the Sea -- tChapter 5. Horizontal Treason: Jean Genet's Funeral Rites -- tChapter 6. "Every woman adores a Fascist": Marguerite Duras, Sylvia Plath, and Feminist Visions of Fascism -- tConclusion. "This Cellar of the Present" -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSalvador Dalí's autobiography confesses that "Hitler turned me on in the highest," while Sylvia Plath maintains that "every woman adores a Fascist." Susan Sontag's famous observation that art reveals the seamier side of fascism in bondage, discipline, and sexual deviance would certainly appear to be true in modernist and postwar literary texts. How do we account for eroticized representations of fascism in anti-fascist literature, for sexual desire that escapes the bounds of politics?Laura Frost advances a compelling reading of works by D. H. Lawrence, Virginia Woolf, Jean Genet, Georges Bataille, Marguerite Duras, and Sylvia Plath, paying special attention to undercurrents of enthrallment with tyrants, uniforms, and domination. She argues that the first generation of writers raised within psychoanalytic discourse found in fascism the libidinal unconscious through which to fantasize acts—including sadomasochism and homosexuality—not permitted in a democratic conception of sexuality without power relations. By delineating democracy's investment in a sexually transgressive fascism, an investment that persists to this day, Frost demonstrates how politics enters into fantasy. This provocative and closely-argued book offers both a fresh contribution to modernist literature and a theorization of fantasy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFascism in literature. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSex in literature. 4aEurope. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172425140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724251423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724251/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK